→ John Pierpont Morgan. J.P. Morgan's middle name \"Pierpont\" commemorates this descent from the Pierpont family of New Haven — founded by Rev. James Pierpont, who married Mary Hooker (H00034). Thomas Hooker's great-great-great-granddaughter's grandson became the most powerful financier in American history.","tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 388"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00494","children_ids":["H00976","HD1550","H00977","H00978","H00979","H00980","H00981","H00982","H00983","H00984","X00998"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1767,"date_month":12,"date_day":26},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"H00451","date_year":1789,"date_month":2,"date_day":26,"children_ids":["HD0558","HD0559","HD0560","HD0561","HD0562","HD0563"]}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"John Pierpont","notes":"Sources also give surname as \"Pierrepont\" — alternate spelling","first_name":"John","last_name":"Pierpont","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Great-grandfather of J.P. Morgan","body":"His great-grandson was John Pierpont Morgan (1837-1913), the financier whose name 'J.P. Morgan' carries forward this Pierpont line. Through his son James Pierpont and grandson John Pierpont the poet, the name traveled four generations to one of America's most consequential bankers."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lived in old Pierpont mansion, New Haven","body":"Timothy Dwight described him as 'a large landholder who lived in the old family-mansion at New Haven.' He had ten children, of whom only four reached adulthood and only three married."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Family later restored 'Pierrepont' French spelling","body":"He was born 'Pierpont' but late in his life, around 1802, Hezekiah Beers Pierpont requested the family restore the original French 'Pierrepont' spelling. Hezekiah did not adopt it himself for business reasons; descendants split between the two spellings thereafter."}],"slug":"john-pierpont-1740"},"X00494":{"id":"X00494","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1744},"death":{"year":1835},"gender":"female","parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00388","date_year":1767,"date_month":12,"date_day":26,"children_ids":["H00976","HD1550","H00977","H00978","H00979","H00980","H00981","H00982","H00983","H00984","X00998"]}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Beers","first_name":"Sarah","maiden_name":"Beers","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"She buried seven children and lived to ninety","body":"Sarah Beers married John Pierpont and bore ten children, but only four reached adulthood; she named three daughters Sarah and lost two as infants and the third at fourteen. She lived to ninety, outliving her husband by thirty years."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"The British seized her home as a hospital","body":"During the 1779 British invasion of New Haven, soldiers raided the house her husband John Pierpont had built and took it for use as a hospital and headquarters. The home stood at the center of the town's worst wartime days."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"Her brother guarded the captured spy Major André","body":"Sarah's brother, Captain Nathan Beers, commanded the guard over the British spy Major John André at his trial and execution in 1780. André's hanging, in the wake of Benedict Arnold's treason, was among the most talked-of events of the war."}],"slug":"sarah-beers-1744"},"HD0419":{"id":"HD0419","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1712,"month":5,"day":26,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1741,"month":9,"day":29,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"X00126","mother_id":"H00034"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 122"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM014","plot_notes":"Center Church on the Green Churchyard, New Haven, Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00146","children_ids":["H00387","H00388"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1741,"date_year":1737,"date_month":2,"date_day":9}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Hezekiah Pierpont","first_name":"Hezekiah","maiden_name":"Pierpont","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Root of the Brooklyn Pierrepont line"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"The family genealogy runs through him","body":"The youngest son died at twenty-nine, yet the Pierrepont genealogy devotes its central chapter to his line — which led to the Brooklyn Pierreponts. His widow Lydia Hemingway remarried to Theophilus Morgan."}],"slug":"hezekiah-p